title: For Sale:  Complete AR-15, with Ammo and Mags
postcontent: I built this rifle a few years ago, but sadly it rarely gets used.  I've put about 500 rounds through it and haven't had any stoppages or malfunctions.  I spent somewhere in the range of $2,500 to $3,000 just on the rifle alone, and for $1,800 I will include 13 magazines and about 1200 rounds.Here's the parts list for the rifle:Spikes Forged Honey Badger Lower Spikes Forged M4 Upper Spikes Nickel Boron Coated BCG Spikes Receiver Extension/Buffer Tube Spikes ST-T2 Buffer Spikes Lower Parts Kit Magpul MBUS Sights (Front and Rear) Magpul K2 Grip Magpul CTR Stock Magpul MOE Trigger Guard Noveske N4 Light Barrel 16" Noveske NSR Handguard 13.5" Noveske QD Receiver Endplate Noveske NSR Panel Kits (2) Noveske NSR QD Mount Norgon Ambi Magazine CatchOdin Works XMR Gen 3 Magazine Release Button BAD-CASS Safety/Selector Lantac Dragon Muzzle Brake Raptor Ambi Charging Handle Geissele Super Dynamic Enhanced Trigger (2 Stage, 3.5lb)Primary Arms 1-6 Scope with PA MountIn addition, I have a handful of miscellaneous parts that will also go with the rifle.Noveske NSR Bipod/Sling Stud Noveske NSR 9 Section RailSpikes Mil Spec Magazine ReleaseMagpul MS4 Sling(12) Magpul 30 Round PMag(1) Magpul Windowed 30 Round PMagDanish 5.56 900 Round Ammo CanAny small pins or parts that were extrasAs far as ammo, there right around 1,200 rounds total.  New in box inside the ammo can are:600 Rounds Mil Spec M855 from Denmark240 Rounds Monarch 55gr Steel CaseThe rest is loaded in to the magazines.  It is either more Danish M855, Monarch Steel Case, or Lake City M855 (which you can tell apart from the Danish by the green tip or the LC head stamp).The only problem that anything has is the Primary Arms scope.  The epoxy on the rear objective lens/tube dried up and/or cracked, and the tube will turn when you turn the zoom lever.  If you release the rear MBUS sight, it usually will hold it in place.  Primary Arms (located in Pearland if you weren't aware) advertises a lifetime warranty, but between how little the rifle was used, and how little free time I have, I never got around to bringing it in.  To be clear, the scope is still completely functional, the one part can just be unthreaded off.The extended scope lever was one I designed and 3D printed after I saw there was only one aftermarket option available, and it has abysmal reviews (it often broke during initial installation).  It makes adjusting the zoom level significantly easier and faster (how hard it was to turn the zoom lever was the only real complaint I've had with this Primary Arms scope).  It's printed from XT-CF20, a carbon fiber reinforced filament.  It can support the entire weight of the rifle and not bend.  It's a friction fit that is very secure, but can easily be removed with a smal light hammer/mallet (strongly recommend a plastic/rubber tipped one so you don't scratch the scope).If you need any more details or pictures, feel free to ask.
